January 24 – Project Kickoff
On this day, we started brainstorming ideas for the robot. We thought about what we wanted it to do and decided it should be able to see objects using a camera. We also chose to use the HuskyLens camera for color recognition.


January 25–31 – Robot Design
During these days, we designed the robot. We thought about what the structure would look like and where the components would go. We also tested different parts to see which configuration was the most stable.


February (all month) – Construction
This month, we focused on building the robot. We built the chassis and attached the wheels and motors. We also made sure it was well-balanced so it wouldn’t tip over.
Little by little, we improved the structure to make it more durable.


March (through the 30th) – Electronics and Camera
During this period, we installed the electronic components. We connected the controller and the battery and organized the wires.
We also mounted the HuskyLens camera and adjusted it so it could see objects clearly. We ran tests to make sure it worked properly.


April 6–11 – Programming
During these days, we began programming the robot. We used code so that the camera could detect colors and provide us with information such as the position (X, Y) and size of objects.
We tested the code several times and corrected errors.


April 21–24 – Final Testing
During these last few days, we conducted final tests on the robot. We checked that everything was working properly and adjusted some details.
